@flexiarg peeragogy/par
@title Close Each Gathering With a Brief Self-Review
@keywords par, paragogical-action-review, after-action-review, retrospective, meta-cognition, self-assessment, eat-own-cooking, sprint-review, five-questions
@audience peer-learning facilitators, project conveners, podcast hosts, workshop runners
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/heartbeat peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/discerning-a-pattern collaboration-coherence/navel-gazing]

! conclusion: Every gathering of co-learners or co-producers benefits from a short self-applied review at the end.  The Paragogical Action Review (PAR) is a five-question structure adapted from the US Army's After Action Review and made more peer-directed: review intention → establish what's happening → what are the different perspectives → what did we learn or change → what else should we change going forward.  The discipline is to run it on yourselves about the activity you just did, not on someone else about something they did.
  + context: A peer-learning group has just held a session — a meeting, a podcast recording, a workshop, a writing sprint.  Without a closing review, learnings stay in individual heads, the group cannot see itself, and the next iteration is built on guesswork.  PAR's contribution is a short, structured loop that takes 5–15 minutes and makes the group's understanding of what just happened legible to itself.  The "eat your own cooking" stance — applying the practice to the artifact that documents the practice — is what distinguishes PAR from a sprint review handed to a manager or a retrospective held with someone outside the work.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: extending the work ↔ closing the loop.
    Real: the work the group came to do is the obvious priority; reviewing the work feels like extra time.  But without the review, learnings dissipate and the next iteration repeats the same surprises.  Extending the working time without ever closing the loop produces a series of incomplete experiences, not a learning trajectory.
    Irreducible: the people best positioned to learn from a session are the participants in it, not an outside reviewer.  They have the context.  But participants are also the most tired by the end, and the most tempted to skip the closing.
    Active: the pull recurs at every session boundary, and is strongest when the session went well (the group feels accomplished and wants to coast on the feeling) or badly (the group wants to escape).
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Five-question close in-broadcast: run all five PAR questions in the last 10 minutes of the session itself.  Highest-fidelity: everyone is still present and the context is fresh.  Cost: extends session length; some attendees won't stay.
    (2) Off-broadcast continuation: end the headline session at the planned time, and convene PAR as an after-party for those who can stay.  Lower-pressure for newcomers; risks splitting the group's reflexive layer from its public layer.
    (3) Async PAR via shared doc: post the five questions to a shared document, gather responses over 24 hours.  Works for distributed groups; loses some of the spoken-conversation texture.
    (4) Single-question micro-PAR: when full PAR feels heavy, ask just one — typically "what did we learn or change?" — to keep the loop alive without the full structure.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the group can name, in their own voices, what they learned in the session and what they would do differently next time.  Failing when: the closing minutes are reserved for thanks and goodbyes only, and learnings stay implicit.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Recurring surprises: the same thing surprises the group across multiple sessions because no review captured it the first time.
    - Reflexive-layer atrophy: the group can run the activity but not articulate what it does or what it has learned about doing it.
    - Newcomer disorientation: incoming participants get no easy way to understand what this group has been learning together.
    - Public/private mismatch: the group's public artifacts (recordings, blog posts) describe an activity; the group's actual learnings live only in side channels.
